Supplementary
	Guidance 
		The Registrar may give guidance about how the Registrar proposes toexercise the functions under this Part.
		The Registrar may do so, in particular, by publishing guidance—
			as to cases which the Registrar would, or would not, regard as fallingwithin any of the exceptions in Part 1 of Schedule 1;
			otherwise as to the circumstances in which the Registrar would, or wouldnot, consider that a person is carrying on the business of consultantlobbying;
			as to the circumstances in which the Registrar would—
			include in the register a statement under section 6(6)(a), or
			remove a person’s entry from the register;
			as to the circumstances in which the Registrar would consider itappropriate to impose a civil penalty;
			about how the amount of a civil penalty will be determined.
		The Registrar may publish—
			revisions to any guidance published under this section;
			replacement guidance.
		Publication under this section is to be—
			on a website, and
			in such other form or forms as the Registrar considers appropriate.
	Charges 
		The Registrar may impose charges for or in connection with the making,updating and maintenance of entries in the register.
		The charges are to be determined by or in accordance with regulations.
		In making the regulations, the Minister must seek to ensure that the totalpaid to the Registrar in charges is sufficient to offset the total of thecosts incurred by the Registrar in exercising the functions under this Part(whether or not those costs are directly connected with the keeping of theregister).
		If a charge imposed for making an application or a return to the Registraris not paid, the Registrar may treat the application or return as not havingbeen made.
		The Registrar must pay into the Consolidated Fund any sums received inrespect of charges under this section.
	Power to make further provision
		Regulations may make such provision as the Minister considers appropriatefor the purposes of carrying into effect any provision of this Part.
		Regulations under subsection (1) may in particular make provision (orfurther provision) about—
			the date from which an entry in the register is to take effect;
			the form and content of information returns under section 5;
			the exercise of the Registrar’s powers under section 6(6);
			the removal of entries in other circumstances;
			the minimum period between the date on which an information notice isserved and the date which must be specified under section 9(4)(b);
			other matters which must be specified in an information notice;
			the cancellation of notices under section 9(7).
		Regulations under subsection (1) may make provision permitting or requiringthe Commissioners for Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs to supply to theRegistrar, on request, such information regarding any person who is, or isrequired to be, registered under the Value Added Tax Act 1994 as is specifiedin the regulations.
	Regulations 
		Any reference in this Part to regulations is to regulations made by theMinister.
		Regulations under this Part may make such consequential, supplementary,incidental or transitional provision as the Minister considers appropriate,including provision amending or modifying the provisions of this Part.
		Regulations under this Part may make different provision for differentpurposes or cases.
		Regulations under this Part are to be made by statutory instrument.
		A statutory instrument containing any of the following regulations may notbe made unless a draft of the instrument has been laid before, and approved bya resolution of, each House of Parliament—
			regulations under section 4(5)(a) or 5(4);
			the first regulations to be made under each of sections 11(3) and 17(3);
			regulations under this Part which amend or modify the provisions of thisPart.
		Any other statutory instrument containing regulations under this Part is tobe subject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House ofParliament.
	Interpretation 
		In this Part—
			  * “consultant lobbyist” means a person who carries on the business of consultant lobbying; 
			  * “employee” means an individual who works under a contract of employment; 
			  * to “engage in lobbying” means to make a communication within section 2(3) on behalf of another person or persons; 
			  * “information notice” means a notice under section 9; 
			  * “the Minister” means the Secretary of State or the Lord President of the Council; 
			  * “payment”, “in return for payment” and references to receiving payment are to be read in accordance with paragraphs 5 to 7 of Schedule 1; 
			  * “penalty notice” means a notice under section 16; 
			  * “quarter” means each period of three months beginning with 1 January, 1 April, 1 July or 1 October; 
			  * “registered person” means a person entered in the register of consultant lobbyists; 
			  * “the Tribunal” means— 
			the First-tier Tribunal, or
			in any case where it is determined by or under Tribunal Procedure Rules thatthe appeal is to be heard by the Upper Tribunal, that Tribunal.
		Where the Registrar is required or permitted to serve a notice on a person,this is to be effected—
			if the person is a registered company (within the meaning of the CompaniesAct 2006), by sending it by post to the company’s registered office;
			if the person is an individual, by delivering it in person, by sending itby post to the individual’s last known place of residence or business, or byleaving it at that place;
			in any other case, by sending it by post to the last known main address ofthat person;
				(but this does not prevent the Registrar from sending additional copies of thenotice by whatever means the Registrar considers appropriate).

Constituency limits
	Part 6 of the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000(controls relating to third party national election campaigns) is amended asfollows.
	In section 94 (limits on controlled expenditure by third parties)—
		in subsection (1), after “Northern Ireland” insert “, or in particularparliamentary constituencies,”;
		in subsection (2)—
		after “part of the United Kingdom” (the first time it occurs) insert “or aparliamentary constituency”;
		after “part of the United Kingdom” (the second time it occurs) insert “orparliamentary constituency”;
		in subsection (6)—
		in paragraph (a), after “part of the United Kingdom” insert “or aparticular parliamentary constituency”;
		in the words after paragraph (b), after “part of the United Kingdom”insert “or parliamentary constituency”;
		in subsection (10), after paragraph (e) (as inserted by section 28) insert—
		any reference to controlled expenditure being incurred in a parliamentaryconstituency shall be construed in accordance with paragraph 2A of Schedule10.”
	In section 96 (returns as to controlled expenditure)—
		in subsection (2), after paragraph (a) insert—
		a statement listing each constituency (if any) in which the controlledexpenditure incurred by or on behalf of the third party during that periodexceeded 0.04% of the total of the maximum campaign expenditure limits inEngland, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland;
		a statement showing, for each constituency listed under paragraph (aa),all payments made in respect of controlled expenditure incurred by or onbehalf of the third party during that period in that constituency;”;
		in subsection (3)(a), after “subsection (2)(a)” insert “or (ab)”.
	Schedule 10 (limits on controlled expenditure) is amended in accordancewith subsections (5) to (9).
	After paragraph 2 insert—
	“Attribution of expenditure to different parliamentary constituencies
		2A(1)For the purposes of this Schedule controlled expenditure incurred by oron behalf of any recognised third party shall (subject to the followingprovisions of this paragraph) be attributed to each parliamentary constituencyin equal proportions.
		Controlled expenditure whose effects are wholly or substantially confinedto any particular constituencies or constituency—
			shall be attributed to those constituencies in equal proportions, or
			shall be attributed solely to that constituency,
			as the case may be.
		For the purposes of sub-paragraph (2), the effects of controlledexpenditure are wholly or substantially confined to any particularconstituencies or constituency if they have no significant effects in anyother constituency or constituencies.
		References in this Schedule to controlled expenditure “in” a particularconstituency are accordingly to controlled expenditure which is to beattributed to that constituency in accordance with this paragraph.”
		After paragraph 3(2) insert—
		“(2A)The limit applying to controlled expenditure which is incurred by or onbehalf of a recognised third party in the relevant period in any particularparliamentary constituency is 0.05% of the total of the maximum campaignexpenditure limits in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.”
		In paragraph 9 (combined limits where parliamentary election pending)—
			in sub-paragraph (1)(a), for “a limit” substitute “limits”;
			in sub-paragraph (2)(b), for “limit” substitute “limits”;
			after sub-paragraph (3) insert—
			“(3A)Subject to sub-paragraphs (5) to (7), the limit applying to controlledexpenditure which is incurred by or on behalf of the recognised third party inthe relevant period in any particular parliamentary constituency is therelevant proportion of the limit mentioned in paragraph 3(2A).
			(3B)For this purpose “the relevant proportion” means—
			[![](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001)](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001?view=plain)
			where—
				  * A is the number of days in the relevant period;
				  * B is the number of days in the period which is the relevant period for the purposes of paragraph 3.”;
			in sub-paragraph (4), for “sub-paragraph (3)” substitute “sub-paragraphs(3) to (3B)”;
			after sub-paragraph (5) insert—
			“(5A)Where two parliamentary general elections are pending during differentparts of any such period as is mentioned in sub-paragraph (2)—
			the limit applying to controlled expenditure which is incurred by or onbehalf of the recognised third party in the first relevant period in anyparticular parliamentary constituency is the relevant proportion of the limitmentioned in paragraph 3(2A), and
			the limit applying to controlled expenditure which is incurred by or onbehalf of the recognised third party in the second relevant period in anyparticular parliamentary constituency is the relevant proportion of the limitmentioned in paragraph 3(2A).
			(5B)For these purposes “the relevant proportion” means—
			[![](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001)](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001?view=plain)
			where—
				  * A is the number of days in the first relevant period or (as the case may be) the second relevant period;
				  * B is the number of days in the period which is the relevant period for the purposes of paragraph 3.”;
			in sub-paragraphs (6) and (7), for “sub-paragraph (5)” substitute “sub-paragraphs (5) to (5B)”.
		In paragraph 10 (combination of limit under paragraph 9 and other limit)—
			in sub-paragraph (1)—
			for “a limit” (in both places) substitute “limits”;
			after “9(3)” insert “to (3B)”;
			after “9(5)” insert “to (5B)”;
			in sub-paragraph (2), for “limit” (in both places) substitute “limits”;
			after sub-paragraph (3) insert—
			“(3A)The limit applying to controlled expenditure which is incurred by or onbehalf of the recognised third party during the combined period in anyparticular parliamentary constituency is the relevant proportion of the limitmentioned in paragraph 3(2A).
			(3B)For this purpose “the relevant proportion” means—
			[![](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001)](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001?view=plain)
			where—
				  * A is the number of days in the combined period;
				  * B is the number of days in the period which is the relevant period for the purposes of paragraph 3.”
		In paragraph 11 (combination of parliamentary general election and otherelection, or elections, falling within paragraphs 4 to 8)—
			in sub-paragraph (1), for “a limit” substitute “limits”;
			in sub-paragraph (2), for “limit” (in both places) substitute “limits”;
			after sub-paragraph (4) insert—
			“(4A)The limit applying to controlled expenditure which is incurred by or onbehalf of the recognised third party during the combined period in anyparticular parliamentary constituency is the relevant proportion of the limitmentioned in paragraph 3(2A).
			(4B)For this purpose “the relevant proportion” means—
			[![](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001)](/ukpga/2014/4/images/ukpga_20140004_en_001?view=plain)
			where—
				  * A is the number of days in the combined period;
				  * B is the number of days in the period which is the relevant period for the purposes of paragraph 3.”
